{{Infobox NRHP | name = Francis M. Drexel School | nrhp_type = | image = Old Drexel School Exterior.jpg | caption = Exterior of the Drexel School in 1897 | location = 1800 S. Sixteenth St., [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|55|42|N|75|10|21|W|region:US-PA_type:edu|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Philadelphia#Pennsylvania#USA | built = 1888 | architect = [[Joseph Anschutz]]; Charles O'Neill, Jr. | architecture = Late Victorian | added = December 4, 1986 | area = {{Convert|1|acre}} | mpsub = {{NRHP url|id=64000730|title=Philadelphia Public Schools TR}} | refnum = 86003272<ref name=nris>{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }}
The '''Francis M. Drexel School''' was a historic [[school]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]. Located along Sixteenth Street, the school was designed by [[Joseph Anschutz]] and built under the direction of Charles O'Neill, Jr.<ref name=nris /> The three-[[storey|story]] brick building was built in a regular rectangular plan in the [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] style of architecture, with three [[chimney]]s dominating its [[facade]].<ref name=nomination>Mintz, Elizabeth.<!-- "B. Mintz" on the form; full name is derived from the "mps" reference, page 16 --> ''[{{NRHP-PA|H052193_01D.pdf}} Pennsylvania Historic Resources Survey: Francis M. Drexel School]''. [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]]: [[Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission]], August 1986. Accessed 2010-02-15.</ref>{{Rp|2}}
The school was named for [[Francis Martin Drexel]], whose son, banker and philanthropist [[Anthony J. Drexel]], founded [[Drexel University]] two years after the construction of the school.
==The school== [[File:Francis M. Drexel School Interior.jpg|thumb|left|Interior of the school in 1897. Gaslights hang down from the ceiling, and the moveable classroom walls have been folded and stored.]] At the time of the Drexel School's construction, Philadelphia's school system had a decentralized administration, with Drexel being a part of the Twenty-sixth Section.<ref name="custis"/> The school buildings, however, were designed by the central administration.<ref name=mps />
The Drexel family was intensely involved with education at this time. Anthony J. Drexel, as the partner of [[J.P. Morgan]], was an internationally important financier, and as the partner of [[George William Childs|George W. Childs]], publisher of the Philadelphia ''[[Public Ledger (Philadelphia)|Public Ledger]]'', was influential in local affairs as well. He was a close friend of Childs, and together they worked to offer free or inexpensive education to the working class. According to Childs, Drexel gave "many munificent gifts to established educational and charitable institutions," as well as founding and endowing the Drexel Institute, which later became [[Drexel University]].<ref>Childs, George W., in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]'', reprinted as "Two Noble Lives" in the [https://books.google.com/books?id=s-MBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA102#v=onepage&q=&f=false Pennsylvania School Journal], V. 42, Sept. 1893, pp. 102-104.</ref> Drexel's orphaned niece, [[Katherine Drexel]], sought advice from Childs and Drexel on her plans to become a nun in the service of educating [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]]s and [[African-American]]s. This work led to her [[beatification]] by Pope John II.<ref>{{cite book | last =Rottenberg | first =Dan | title =The Man Who Made Wall Street: Anthony J. Drexel and the Rise of Modern Finance | publisher =University of Pennsylvania Press | year =2006 | page =262 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=ZL-BpElFOVwC | doi = | id ={{ISBN|081221966X}}, 9780812219661 }} Ch. 13 "Two Social Revolutionaries" pp. 149-161</ref> Two other nieces, Elizabeth Drexel Smith and Louise Drexel Morrell, founded and endowed the St. Francis Industrial School at Eddington, Pennsylvania in 1888.<ref name="catholic">{{cite book | last =Loughlin | first =James F. | authorlink1= James F. Loughlin |editor=Charles George Herbermann | title =The Catholic Encyclopedia, Volume 5 | publisher =Encyclopedia Press | year =1913 | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=-aSQNo8kNqIC&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q=&f=false }}, p. 159</ref> The George W. Childs School, also designed by Anschutz, was built in 1894 just three blocks north of the Francis M. Drexel School.<ref name=mps />{{Rp|33}}
Completed in 1889,<ref name=nomination />{{Rp|2}} the Drexel School included features common to late nineteenth-century Philadelphia schools. Earlier schools were generally built entirely of [[brick]], and the 1870s saw the introduction of [[Stonemasonry|stone]] schools, but schools built between 1883 and 1900, including Drexel, typically combined brick walls and [[brownstone]] finishing.<ref name=mps>Moak, Jefferson M., et al. ''{{NRHP url|id=64000730|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Philadelphia Public Schools Thematic Resources}}''. [[National Park Service]], August 1986. Accessed 2010-02-15.</ref>{{Rp|6}}
Anschutz worked in the tradition of Samuel Sloan's "Philadelphia Plan" of school architecture: On each floor, classrooms opened onto a single corridor, and were divided by moveable partitions. Coatrooms were provided in each classroom. Stairways and other non-classroom space were located at the end of the corridor, near the outside of the building.<ref name=mps/>{{Rp|9–10}} The architectural plans closely follow these principles. The school's windows were enlarged in 1914, and in 1922, lighting was changed from gas to electric.<ref>Original architectural drawings are available online at www.thedrexelschool.com sub-page "Blueprints"</ref>
Although it originally housed classes for both [[Elementary school|elementary]] and [[Secondary school|secondary]] students, Drexel was built at a time when school boards were beginning to open separate schools for different purposes.<ref name = "custis">Custis, John Trevor. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=cggUAAAAIAAJ The Public Schools of Philadelphia: Historical, Biographical, Statistical.]'' Philadelphia: Burk & McFetridge, 1897, pp. 429-435.</ref><ref name=mps />{{Rp|11}} It remained in use by the [[School District of Philadelphia|Philadelphia Public Schools]] into the late twentieth century.<ref name=nomination />{{Rp|1}}
==Recognition and demolition== In 1986, the Francis Drexel School was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in recognition of its architectural significance.<ref name=nris /> While many Philadelphia schools had been modeled on the Drexel School in the late nineteenth century, most had been destroyed or significantly remodeled; only Drexel and two other schools remained in a condition similar to that of their original construction.<ref name=nomination />{{Rp|2}} Fifty-two other Philadelphia schools, including five designed by Anschutz,<ref name=mps />{{Rp|11}} were added to the Register on the same day as part of the Philadelphia Public Schools [[multiple property submission]].<ref name=nris />
The Drexel School was demolished in February, 2010.<!--why? this should be explained--><ref>View of the school provided by [[:File:Drexel School 3.JPG|this]] picture</ref>
